[{"id":41719,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["a macroscopic region with saturation magnetization.","a macroscopic region with consecutive magnetic dipoles oriented in opposite direction.","a macroscopic region with zero magnetization.","a macroscopic region with randomly oriented magnetic dipoles."],"answer":0,"solution":"In a ferromagnetic material, below the curie temperature, a domain is defined as a macroscopic region with saturation magnetization.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41722,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>J</mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>J</mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>J</mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>11</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>J</mtext></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#964;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>MBsin&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>018</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.018</mo></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>sin</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#952;</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.018</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.06</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.5</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.64</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>A</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>W</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#916;U</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">U</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></msub><mo>&#8722;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">U</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>MB</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cos</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mn>180</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup><mo>&#8722;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>MB</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cos</mi><msup><mn>0</mn><mo>&#8728;</mo></msup></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>MB</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.6</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.06</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>072</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (04 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41693,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>%</mo></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>%</mo></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>It is given that&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#967;</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>The permeability is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>r</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>&#967;</mi><mi>m</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn></math>.</p><p>The magnetic field is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mi>r</mi></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></math></p><p>Hence, percentage increase in magnetic field is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>%</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><msub><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>B</mi></mstyle><mn>0</mn></msub></mstyle><mfenced><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>%</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>%</mo></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41705,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8cb9ce9a-72ba-4b3f-8f81-e25c10734098-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 139px;\" /></p><p>Emf produced is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><msub><mi>L</mi><mo>&#8869;</mo></msub><msub><mi>v</mi><mo>&#8869;</mo></msub></math></p><p>We know&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>H</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>tan</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>, so&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math></p><p>Then,&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>20</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>20</mn></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (27 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":41725,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math><mn>3.6</mn></math>","<math><mn>1.8</mn></math>","<math><mn>1.2</mn></math>","<math><mn>0.7</mn></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> be the respective oscillation frequencies respectively for&nbsp;<math><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math> and <math><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>&nbsp;dip. Then,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mi>M</mi><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mi>I</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#960;</mi></mrow></mfrac><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mi>M</mi><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>cos</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mi>I</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>f</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msup><mn>30</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mn>40</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>900</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>1600</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0.688</mn><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>0.7</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41752,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["high retentivity and high coercivity","low retentivity and low coercivity","high retentivity and low coercivity","low retentivity and high coercivity"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":41739,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>&#60;</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></math>but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>&#8800;</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>s</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8211;</mo><mi>B</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"In diamagnetic material, the magnetic field strength decreases. So, in a perfect diamagnetic,&nbsp;it has to be zero.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (19 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":41751,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["$2 \\mathrm{~s}$","$2 / 3 \\mathrm{~s}$","$2 \\sqrt{3} \\mathrm{~s}$","$2 / \\sqrt{ } 3 \\mathrm{~s}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Time period of vibration, $T=2 \\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{1}{M B}}$\nWhere $\\ell=$ moment of inertia of magnet, $\\mathrm{M}=$ magnetic moment $\\mathrm{I}=\\frac{\\mathrm{m} \\ell^2}{12}$ and $\\mathrm{M}=$ pole strength $\\times \\ell$\n$$\nI^{\\prime}=\\frac{1}{12}\\left(\\frac{m}{3}\\right)\\left(\\frac{\\ell}{3}\\right)^2 \\times 3=\\frac{\\mathrm{l}}{9}\n$$\nand $M^{\\prime}=$ pole strength (will remain the same) $\\times(\\ell / 3) \\times 3=M$.\n$$\n\\mathrm{T}^{\\prime}=\\frac{\\mathrm{T}}{\\sqrt{9}}=\\frac{2}{9} \\mathrm{~s} .\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":41689,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Component of the magnetic field perpendicular to the plane of fan blades, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>v</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>sin</mi><mn>30</mn><mo>°</mo><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math></p><p>Angular frequency, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ω</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>π</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>f</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>π</mi></mrow><mn>60</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>1200</mn><mo> </mo><mi>rad</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo> </mo><mi>rad</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>Therefore, induced EMF</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ε</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mi>ω</mi><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>×</mo><mn>40</mn><mi>π</mi><mo>×</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>32</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":41729,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Magnetic Properties of Matter","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1.8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3.6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1.3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The horizontal and vertical components of earth&#39;s magnetic field (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>H</mi></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub></math>) are related as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>H</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>tan</mi><mi>&#952;</mi></math></p><p>Here, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>H</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>18</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>H</mi></msub><mi>tan</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>H</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>18</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mo>&#8757;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>tan</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></math></p></blockquote><blockquote><p>Now, when the external force&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>F</mi></math> is applied, to keep the needle stays in horizontal position is shown below,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d24e4fa9-330e-4dc2-b590-8a875bed2160-image.png\" style=\"width: 305px; height: 191px;\" /></p><p>Taking torque at point <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>P</mi></math>,&nbsp;we get</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>m</mi><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>F</mi><mi>l</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>m</mi><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>V</mi></msub></math></p><p>Substituting the given values, we get</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>18</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>48</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null}]